Q#,Type,Question,Option A,Option B,Option C,Option D,Answer,Explanation
1,MCQ,How can the responder identify the rogue publisher's connection event in the Mosquitto broker logs?,By searching for client connections with an unauthorized IP address or duplicate client ID.,By monitoring the CPU usage of the broker.,By checking for TLS handshake errors.,By reviewing the HTTP GET requests in the broker logs.,Option A,The broker logs record the source IP and client ID for all client connection events. Comparing these against a known authorized baseline reveals the rogue entity.
2,MCQ,What characteristic of the injected payload made it stand out as an anomaly?,The payload was encrypted.,An impossible rate-of-change from the slow-changing solar curve.,The payload was formatted in XML instead of JSON.,The payload length was too small.,Option B,Physical solar panels generate power along a smooth solar curve. An instantaneous jump from ~45 kW to 150 kW represents a physical impossibility, signaling a data integrity issue.
3,MCQ,Which Mosquitto configuration allowed the unauthorized publisher to write data to the telemetry topic?,Enforced TLS client certificate verification.,The use of an ACL rule pattern readwrite grid/solar/site7/# without enforcing username authentication.,A firewall rule blocking inbound TCP traffic.,Running the broker on port 8883.,Option B,Permitting anonymous connections and using wildcards/broad patterns in the ACL without client ID verification allowed the rogue client to connect and publish.
4,Fill in the Blank,Enter the exact rogue client ID as found in the broker connect log,,,,,rogue_solar_client,The broker logs show the connection of a client with this ID.
5,Fill in the Blank,Enter the exact first forged kW payload value published by the rogue client as recorded in the broker log,,,,,150.00,The first entry in the broker log originating from the rogue client contains a payload value of 150.00 kW.
